{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/0022225470A/1930051901/0249.xml":{"full_text":"Lamont Says United States Business Should Be Normal in Few Months\nPRESENTTRENO\nSHOWS RISE\nstem i\nI\nUnderlying Conditions Called\nGood, With Steel, Utilities, j\nConstruction on Upgrade\nWith a continuation of present i\ntrends in business conditions the\nUnited States should be back to\nnormal within a few months,\nSecretary of Commerce Lamont\ndeclared todaj\nThe normal curve of business 5\nis steadily upward to meet the\nincreasing requirements of greater\npopulation and increased con\nsumption, according |o Lamont, t\nHe said: 1\n\u201cAt this time in 1921 busi\nness was 22 points below the j s\nnormal level, while today it is I s\nbut 6 points below. Underlying\nconditions are better today than\nin 1921 and if the present rate r\nof progress continues, we should\nbe back to normal in two or\nthree months.\u201d\nOperation Satisfactory\nLamont said that the steel\nIndustry expected to \u201ccarry on\u201d\nat about the present rate for\nsometime. He characterized the 80\nper cent of capacity operation In\nthe steel industry as satisfactory, i.\nremarking that such an output\nwas equal to 85 to 100 per cent\ncapacity operation a few years\nago. 1 1\nTotal construction contracts in\nApril amounted in value to $483,-|,\n000,000, the largest since August, I\n1929, he said. This figure, how- i\never, was 25 per cent less than\nApril, 1929, an unusually heavy j\nmonth, while contracts for the\nfirst four months of the year j\naveraged 17 per cent less than\nin 1929. i\nContracts Show Increase\nApril public utilities and public\nworks contracts were valued at\n$149,670,000. compared with $lO5,- j\n350.000 in March and $152,127,000 i\nIn April last year. For the first\nfour months contracts of this t\ncharacter amounted to $452,910.- j\n000, an increase of 30 per cent\nover last year. 1\nReferring to retail trade, La- c\nmont said that 51 per cent of s\nstores reporting showed good to\nexcellent trade in April, while 22 f\nper cent of the same stores made 7\nsimilar reports in March, indicat- r\ning an improvement. i\nRAIL EXTENSION i\nPLAN 0.0\nS\nExaminers of the Interstate 1\nCommerce Commission today 1\nrecommended the Abiline East- s\nem Railroad be authorized to ii\nconstruct 43 miles of new line\nbetween Abiline and Cross Plains.\nTex. 1\nThe city of Abiline intervened\nIn behalf of the road\u2019s applica\ntion, asserting additional railroad\nfacilities are necessary to enable\nthe city to expand.\nThe application was also sup\nported by the Katy railroad on\nthe ground the proposed line\n\u25a0would restore to Abiline the active\nrailroad competition which it en\njoyed prior to the acquisition of\nthe Abiline Southern by the t\nTexas Pacific, and that it\nwould open up new territory. i\n_\u2014 i\nPhiladelphia Gains\nIn Retail Trade J\nPHILADELPHIA. May 19.\u2014Re\ntail sales are increasing week by i\nweek, and have reached a volume t\nwhich compares well with that i\nof a year ago. In line with this\nis the larger volume of check\npayments.\nLocal demand for wool in\ncreases, and firmness is likely to\nbe reflected very soon in retail\nprices of clothing, which have\nbeen low this spring.\nBig industries are doing mod\nerately well, but the greater ac\ntivity Is in outdoor operations.\nPennsylvania, which leads all\nStater in new highway building,\nhas just invited bids for about\nSBOO,OOO additional work.\nWork on large structures is pro\ngressing rapidly in this section.\nNew construction now under way\nhas very materially reduced un\nemployment in this section.\nAs a whole, manufacturing is 1\nestimated to be about B\u20192 per\ncant below the level of last year.l\nThe main dependence of the j\nsteel industry is the project for\na natural gas line from Texas, t\none to Chicago and one to the,\nNorth Atlantic seaboard. Thou- s\nsands of miles of pipe will be re- c\nquired by the time double lines i 5\nare laid. j\nSteel Ingot Output t\nShows Falling Off\nPITTSBURGH, May 19 (U.S.), t\nSteel ingot production at the end\nof last week averaged approxi- s\nmately 77 per cent of capacity, r\ncompared with an average of 80 t\nper cent for the month of April 1\nand with 85 per cent in February, f\nThese figures are based on the a\nfresh finding of capacity, as of\nJanuary 1, last, and official re- t\nports of monthly production. 1\nMarket Gossip\n1\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nThe dullness of the stock market last week convinced many\nimportant operators that it will be perfectly all right to plan long\nsummer vacations and forget financial matters until business shows\na marked improvement. Several active traders already have\nindicated tlfeir intention to abandon operations for the next couple\nof months?. It is logical to assume, in the light of current develop\nments\u2014or lack of developments\u2014that the market will continue\nin its present rut of sluggishness for at least a month, and probably\nthrough three months.\nBankers, brokers and operators who are honest with themselves\nare frank in their admission that there is little hope for brisk\nbusiness before autumn, and it is unlikely that the market will\nbegin to discount the expected improvement before August. Of 1 1\ncourse we will have rallies and occasional active trading days, but\nthe outlook for the summer is a quiet market, featured only by\nunusual apathy on the part of the public and \u201cscalping\u201d tactics on\nthe part of professionals. 1\n\u20141\nDullness Sets Record\nNot since the day preceding the\n\"Coolidge bull market\u201d had such\ndullness been experienced as we\nwitnessed Saturday. Only 790,-\n000 shares changed hands, or at\nthe rate of less than\u2019 2,000,000\nshares for a full five-hour session.\nAt this Yate, it will be some time\nbefore there is any real need foi\nthe new high-speed tickers.\nThe bear element is following\nstrictly the old axiom, \"Never\nsell a dull market short.\u201d\nGovernment vs. Business\nThere is a possibility that busi\nness improvement may get under\nway as soon as Congress is ad\njourned for the summer. In fact,\nit is quite probable that several\npublic utility mergers will take\nplace during the summer months,\nbecause the bankers for several\ncompanies are anxious to avoid\nadverse criticism by legislators.\nIt is generally recognized that\nthe attitude of Washington is\nproving a deterrent to business\nprogress, and that considerable\nside-stepping will be necessary in\norder to put over some pending\ndeals without Government inter\nference.\nThe eyes of the financial and\nbusiness world will be centered on\nUnited Corporation and its as\nsociated concerns during the next\nfew months, for this company is\nnow the acknowledged leader of\nthe utility field.\nRecapitalization Gossip\nYou will hear more persistent\ngossip during the next couple of\nweeks about possibilities of re\ncapitalization in various indus\ntrial concerns. One of the reports\nyou will hear most often is that\nEastman Kodak is about to split\nits stock. There is a difference\nof opinion about the basis of\nsuch split-up. but in well-informed\nquarters it is said that a \"five\nfor-one split would be warranted.\u201d\nThis hint will prove correct, in\nmy opinion. Rumors of split-up\nin case Threshing Machine are\nbecoming more persistent, but I\nhear that there will be no re\ncapitalization in this company\nthis year, or at least until the\nprice of the stock is considerably\nhigher. Remarkable strength and\nactivity of American Tobacco\nseems to bear out the reports\nthat directors are planning an\nearly split-up which would work\ngreatly to advantage of stock\nholders. Tobacco stocks are in\nhigh favor, because past records\nsho wthat they rarely suffer dur\ning periods of business depression.\nLiggett and Myers B is gain\ning in favor every day with those\nIDE CREAM NOW\nBIG BUSINESS\nFew of the millions of con\nsumer of ice cream and few of\nthe dairy farmers of the country\nwho furnish the milk for this\ncommodity realize the magnitude\nof the ice cream industry, O. E.\nReed, chief of the Bureau of\nDairy Industry. Department of\nAgriculture, said today in a radio\naddress. He said:\n\u201cAbout 6,000,009,000 pounds of\nmilk are used annually in the\nmanufacture of this food.\n\u201cThere are about 4,000 ice\ncream factories in the United\nStates today and in 1928 they\nmanufactured more than 1,750,-\n000,000 pounds, or about 348,-\n000,000 gallons of ice cream.\u201d\n\u201cThese ma n u facturers re\nquired the product of about\n1,250,000 cows.\u201d\n\u201cInto the product went 209,-\n000,000 pounds of butterfat;\n243,000,000 pounds of sugar;\n174.000,000 pounds of milk\nsolids other than butterfat and\n5,000,000 pounds of food gela\ntin.\u201d\nPhiladelphia\nBonds on Market\nNEW YORK. May 19.\u2014Natloral\nCity Company is offering, at prices\nto yield about 4.05 per cent, sl,-.\n108,000 city of Philadelphia. Pa.,\nschool district 4Vi per cent bonds, I\ndue in marying amounts from No- 1\nvember 1, 1942, to 1956, inclusive.\nThe bonds are direct obligations\nof the school district, which is co\nterminus with the city of Philadel\nphia, and are payable from unlim\nited taxes on all taxable property\ntherein.\nThe assessed valuation of the\nschool district is $3,451,528,364 and\nnet bonded debt $48,767,209, or less\nthan IV2 per cent of assessed val\nuation. The bonds are exempt\nfrom all Federal income taxes and\nare tax-free in Pennsylvania.\nThey are legal investment for\ntrust funds and savings banks in\nPennsylvania and New York.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nwho have switched out of weaker\nstocks into tobacco shares.\nVanadium\nContinued strength of Vana\ndium is one of the fe features\nof the market these days. While\nspeculative gossip attributes its\nJ strength to various reasons, there\nis no one who seems to have\nt first hand information. Report\nis revived that the stock is prac\ntically cornered and that it will I\nj sell over 150 before long.\nr\nDespite observations that Steel\nCommon has relinquished its\nleadership of the market, the list\ninvariably fails to rally until\nr Steel gives the signal.\nWestern Maryland\n1 Unconfirmed rumors of agree-\nment among leading railroad in\nterests on allocation of control\njI of Western Maryland were as\ni I sumed to be responsible for\nstrength of that issue in an other\nt wise weak market. Early an\ns nouncement of bullish news on\n5 this road is expected soon, as\npredicted in this column early\nj last week.\nDevelopment of a \u201cbull market\u201d i\nin railroad shares is improbable,\nin view of the unfavorable earn-\ni ings statements for the June\nI quarter which will be published\nin July.\nt Standard Brands\nI would not be surprised if\nstandard brands should sag to\nLnew low levels this week. The\n25 cents a share earned in the\nt first quarter of this year was\nf well below the dividend require\nments of 37 V 2 cents. A cut in\n1- the dividend rate at the next\n5 directors\u2019 meeting is not unlikely,\nt\nt Stocks of companies that are\nlarge users of commodities are\nf gaining in favor, due to low\ni prices of commodities and the\nresultant wider profit margins\nfor manufacturing concerns.\nJ Corn Products\nThe low price of com increases\nmargin of profit for Corn Prod-\nucts Refining Company and\nt 1 other companies in its field.\nWhile expected that earnings for\nr the first six months will be fav-\nII orable and that the stock will l\ngain new friends.\nCoca Cola\nt Weakness of sugar prices is\nfavorable to Cocoa Cola, for the\nj company is a large buyer of this;\nj commodity. In addition to this\nfavorable factor, the company\u2019s\nbest season is at hand and profits\nI for this quarter and the Septem-\nber quarter should show substan\n\u00bbI tial gams.\nDROP PREVAILS\nIN CURB LIST\nBy THEODORE KOSLOW\nNEW YORK, May 19.\u2014Curb\nstocks were on the downgrade\ntoday, in what promised to be a\nmore active trading session, and\nmoderately lower levels were the\nrule in the general list.\nSpeculative sentiment had ap-!\nparently been considerably dis-'\nj turbed by the Inability of the\nmarket to move up in the con\nspicuously dull sessions of last\nweek, and it was significant that\nthe heavy turnover in the first\nhour of activity today, prices\nwere sliding off. Whether or not\nthis pointed to a continuance of\nthe downward movement was dif\nficult to say, but the insistent\npressure of the offerings in the\nprincipal trading favorites turned\nmany of the traders who had\nbeen non-committal in previous\nsessions to the bear side of the\nlist, leaning to the theory that\nin view of the professional aspect\nof the market, what won\u2019t go\nup will naturally go down.\nThere were, of course, the isolated\nnumber of exceptions to the gen-1\neral trend, which were able to\u2019\nnegotiate progress on the upside, i\nbecause either of special devel\nopments which were pending, or\ndue to group activity.\nThe utility group as a whole\nI favored the downside, although\n1 declines were larger in many of\nthe more active favorites of re\ncent weeks. Among the issues\nhardest hit were American and\nForeign Power warrants, down\n1% at 59; Consolidated Gas of\nBaltimore, down 2 at 130; Electric\nBond and Share, down 2 at 101\nElectric Power and Light war\nrants, down 3 at 64. and Middle\nWest Utilities, down I*4 at 53%.\nLesser losses were in evidence in\nAmerican Gas and Electric. Amer\nican Superpower. Associated Gas\nand Electric A, Middle West Utili\nties. and Niagara Hudson Power.\nCities Service eased fractionally i\n1 to 36%. for a decline of I\nUTILITIES PLAN\nTO ADVERTISE\nWIDELY\nAmerican business will invest\n$206,000,000 in advertising in 1930.\nstatisticians estimate. E. Paul\nYoung, former chairman of the\ncosts and results committee of the\npublic Utilities Advertising associa\ntion who is attending the twenty\nsixth convention of the Advertis\ning Federation of America, said\ntoday.\nThis represents an increase of\n$20,000,000 over last year and a\nlarge part of it will be contrib\nuted by the public utilities, the\nexpert said.\nIn reviewing the prospects for\nthe coming year. Young said.\n\u201cThe active stimulant of ad\nvertising must be administered\nto business, particularly if any\ndecline in industrial activity is\nto be counter-balanced.\n\u201cIndustrial development and\npublic utilities are linked in\nseparably. The one reflects the\ngrowth and progress of the.\nether Manufacturers every\nwhere arc maintaining, as\nmuch as possible, their advertis\ning appropriations in the face\nof business recession and the\nutilities are setting the pace.\u201d\nYoung predicts a record year\nin the matter of customer owner\nship. He continued:\n\u201cI believe that the total\namount of money invested by\ncustomers in preferred stock of\npublic utilities corporations\nthis year will triple the amount\nInvested similarly in 1929.\nOne reason for this is that\nmany companies have not dis\ntributed any shares for two or\nthree years and a new mass of\ncustomer prospects is waiting\nfor the 1930 issues.\n1 \u201cThis will be a year of expan\nsion, I think, in the utilities\nfield. Advance figures of the\nFederal census show a healthv\nincrease in population and big\ndevelopment in towns and cities.\nNaturally, with more people to\nserve and more territory to\ncover, the utilities will increase\noperating and service facilities\nand the money needed will be\ninvested, in a large degree, by\nutilities customers.\u201d\n2,000 Experts Here\nMore than 2,000 advertising\nexperts arrived in town yesterday\nfor the convention which will con\ntinue throughout the week at the\nWillard Hotel. President Hoover\nwill formally open the session\ntoday with a reception on the\nWhite House lawn shortly before\nnoon.\nDr. Luther Reichelderfer. pres\nident of the Board of District\nCommissioners, will be one of the\nspeakers at the luncheon today.\nChicago Area Shows\nDry Goods Increase\nCHICAGO, May 19. \u2014The un\ndertone in business and industry\ncontinues to show improvement\nwith the exception of the local\nbuilding industry.\nSeveral branches of the electri\ncal industry, valve manufactur\ners and office device companies\nwere on a full-time basis at the\nclose of April. The general level\nof manufacturing activity, both\nin Chicago and Illinois, however,\nremained below normal.\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furnished bv W B Hibbs 4 Co.)\nSALES\nPotomac Electric Cons. ss,\n$4,000@101%.\nWashington Gas ss, 1960. SI,OOO\n@lOl%, $500@101%, sl.ooo@\n102.\nWashington Gas 6s A, sloo@\n101%.\nWashington Railway and Elec\ntric 4s, $3,000 @86%.\nCapital Traction Co., 15@74%,\n10@74%.\nWashington Gas Light, 3@127.\nWashington Railway and Elec\ntric pfd., 20@98, 10@98, 2@98, 10\n@9B.\nLiberty National Bank. 10@216.\nAmerican Security and Trust,\n10@411, 10@411, 10@411.\nMergenthaler Linotype, 8@\n106%, 10@106%.\nThe Carpel Corporation, 50@\n26. 50@26, 50@26, 50@26, 50@\n26%, 50@26%.\nAFTER CALL\nPotomac Electric 5%s pre\nferred. 7@107, 10@107.\nPotomac Electric 6s preferred,\n3@112.\nCapital Traction ss. $500@95%.\nPublic Utility Stocks I Bid Ask.\nAmer Tel 4. Telga 4%5\u2019331100%\nAmer Tel Tel 4%s \u2019391184%\nAm Tel T C\u2019t\u2018l Tr 55...|104%\nAnacostia Pot R R 55..1 83 I\nAna Pot Guar 5s I 94 98\nC P Tel of Va 6s 102\nCap Traction R R 5s 95 95%\nCity Suburban 5s 81 83\nGeorgetown Ges Ist 5s 101 102\nPotomac Elec Cons 5s 101% 102%\nPotomac Elec 6s 1953 108%\nWash Alex Mt V ctf.... 2\nWash Balto An 5s 65\nWashington Gas 58 101% 102%\nWash Gas 6s Series A.... 102 103\nWash Gab 6s Series B 105 105%\nWash Ry Elec 4s I 86%! 87%\nMiscellaneous Bonds I I\nBarber Ross Inc 6%s I 91 93\nCham-Vanblt Hotel 6%5....l 80 I\nchevy chase Club 5%e \u2018IOO\nD. C. Paper Mfr \u00abe.-! 80\nW. M. Cold Storage\u2018is.. 96\nWash Cops Title 6s 80 32%\nPnbllc Utility Stocks I I\nAmar tel Tel\nCapita! Traction Co\n\u2666u* 94s Lt Co bn\nThe National Daily\nI TRUST FORMED\nTO ADVISE\nBUSINESS\nt Abandoning a traditional policy\n,of reserved isolation, the Bank of\n1 England has assumed public 1\ne leadership in the attempt to re-\n8 vive commercial and industrial 1\ni- conditions in Great Britain, ac- 1\ncording to a discussion of this j\n1- situation published by the Com-\ni merce Department today, follow- j\ning a report from American 1\nf Trade Commissioner Roger R.\n1 Townsend at London. 1\nIn taking this stand, the Bank 1\nof England has gone even farther\nr than did the Federal Reserve sys-\ntern, the comparable institution\nin the United States, when the 1\nstock market break was followed j\nby business depression. The re-\nserve system assumed leadership\nin the movement before the\nbreak to prepare for the inevit\nable collapse, and. following that\nfinancial crisis, to ease the money\nmarket and mitigate its effect.\nAbandons Policy\nTownsend said:\n\"The depression into which\nGreat Britain\u2019s basic industries\nr have lapsed during the past\nfew years has induced the Bank\nof England to abandon its\ntraditional policy of reserved\nisolation and to assume public\nleadership.\u201d\nA company, known as the\nSecurities Management Trust, has\nbeen formed under the auspices\nof the bank, with a directorate\nof the government assisted by\nan expert board of business men.\nIts principal object is to assist\nmanufacturing firms with advice\nand guidance in formulating\nschemes for reorganization,\namalgamation, and the acquisi-\ntion of new capital.\nAnother organization. the\nBankers Industrial Development\nCompany, has been formed to\nassist in the development of in\nj dustries. It aims to accomplish I\nj this by helping entire industries.\n!or industrial regions, to reor-;\nganize along modern lines and\nto co-ordinate their activities. It i\nwill not deal with individual\ncompanies, but only with basic\nindustries of major importance.\nP No Capital Furnished\n1- The development company will\ne not .furnish capital for reor\nr ganizations but will act as inter\n-1 mediary for the supply of funds\ne through the usual channels. It\ne was expected this would result\nin new issues of capital being\nfloated in the American market,\nt Officials here were interested\ne in the scheme for the principal\nI reason that Great Britain is\nAmerica\u2019s best customer and this\ncountry\u2019s major source of supply\ni for raw materials. A revival of\n1 business in Great Britain would\nhave an important effect in I\ni* 1 United States and far-reaching\ny reaction throughout the world, i\n,1 Extra Holiday Asked\ni. For Stock Exchange\nNEW YORK. May 19. \u2014The\ns New York Stock Exchange an\ne nounced yesterday that 775 mem\n-1 bers had signed their names to a\n1 petition requesting that the ex\nchange be closed on the Saturday\nfollowing Memorial Day.\nNA W Steamboat |\u201964 1265\nSteamboat Rts Wi.,| 17 17%\nPot Elec Power 6 S pfd \u2018llO% 112\n\u2022Pot Elec Pwr 5%s pfd 1104% 40?% I\n\u2022Wash Ry El Com 1550 I\n\u2022Wash Ry 4 El Pfd I 98 98\nWash Balt An com. I 6 I\nWash Blat A An pfd 7 j\nNational Rank Stock*\nCapital 1360\nColumbia Ids j\nCommercial (stamped) !286 240\nDistrict |215 L 224\nFederal-American 1280 300\nLiberty !\u2019ls \u20182lB\nLincoln 1400 1435\nMetropolitan (370\nRiggs 1610 \u2018535\nSecond 1190 1205\nWashington |260 1260\nTrust Company Stocks I I\nAmer Sec 4 Tr Co 1410 1425\nj Continental Trust 1125 136\nMerchants Bank Trust.... 1125 1130\nNat Savings 4 Trust 1570 1600\nUnion Trust 250 1300\nWashington Loan A- Trust. .1495 \u2018515\nSaving Bank Stocks I 'l\nBank of Bethesda I 60 I 65\nCom. 4 Savings..... 1330 i\nEast Washington ...J 26 I 36\nPot. Savings Bank I 66 I 75\nSec. Sav. 4 Com Bk 1482 500\nSeventh Street \u2018305 I\ni United States %30 I\nI Wash. Mechanics I 50 I\nFire Insurance Stocks i\nAmerican |32i I\nCorcoran 450 I\nFiremen's |3B 144 I\nNational Union *.l 24 I 28\nTitle Insurance Stocks I\nColumbia I 3 I 12\nReal Estate 1160 1....\nTitle Inv Co. Md, com...| 20 I 30\nMiscellaneous Stocks\nBarber Ross Inc. c0m.... 16 20\nChevy Ch. Dairy pfd 103 108\nCol. San Grav pfd 94% 96\nD C Paper Mfg pfd 35 60\nDiet Natl Sec pfd 86 95\nEmer Bromo Selz. \u201cA\".... 31% 33\nFederal Storage pfd 110 125 1\nFed.-Am Co com 30% 32 1\nFed.-Am. Co pfd 100 104\nLanston Monotype 122 126\nMer Tr Stge com 109% 110\nMer Tr stge pfd 100 102\nMergenthaler Lino 106% 1106%\nNatl Mtge Inv pfd 4%l 4%\nPeoples Drug S pfd 108 1109\nPrince Georges Bk 4 Tr... 30 I\nReal Est M 4 G rfd 7 7%\nSecurity Storage |ll4 'll\u00df\ni Ter Ref i- Wh Corp 48 162 j\nThe Carpel Corp I 26%,! 2*\nw Meeh Mtge.com 9%l 10% i\nWash Med Bldg Corp 90 ,10\u00bb\nWdwd 4 Lothrap pfd _...110T%i1U\nwiwiiea tsru\u00bb4.\nMONDAY, MAY 19, 1930\nCORPORATION NEWS\nI -J\nEvidences of treater potentials\ndarninn in the various branches\nof the petroleum industry are\npointed out by Standards Statis\ntics Company of New York, in\nits current survey of that in\ndustry.\nSummarized briefly, they show:\nAssurance of substantial increase\nof volume of demand: adequate\nsource of supply for years to\ncome; greater earnings potential\nities of balanced crude produc\ntion: more efficient allocation of\nrefinerie?: greater concentration\non marketing of products, and,\nlarge scale entrance of the oil\nindustry into the field of natural\ngas distribution.\nA banking group, consisting of\nthe National City Company, Dil\nlon, Reed and Co., Guaranty Com\npany of New York, Harris. Forbes\nand Co., Dominion Securities\nCorporation and the Canadian\nBank of Commerce, is offering at\nprices to yield 4 to 4.85 per cent,\n$13,396,000 City of Toronto, On\ntario. 5 per cent bonds, due in,\nvarying amounts from April 1,\n1931, to 1950, Inclusive.\nNegotiations looking toward\nthe purchase of the assets of the\nCalifornia Wire and Cable Com\npany t by Anaconda Wire and\nCable Company, of California, a\nsubsiduary of Anaconda Wire\nand Cable Company, which have\nbeen pending for some time, has\nbeen completed. Stock will be\nissued by the Anaconda Wire\nand Cable Company, for shares\nof California Wire.\nO\u2019Brian, Potter, Stafford, and\nCompany, members of the New\nYork Stock Exchange announce\nthat D. D. Martin replaces D.\nR. Martin as a special partner\nin the firm.\nMcGraw Hill Publishing Com\npany, Inc., and subsiduary organi\nzation report for the quarter\nending March 31, 1930 net profits\nafter deduction of all charges and\ntaxes, of $534,980, equivalent to\n89 cents per share on the 600,000\nshares of common stock out\nstanding. Net profits for 1929 in\nthe same period were equal to\n86 cents per share.\nDirectors of Twin States Nat\nural Gas Company, have author\nized the issuance of 40.000 addi\ntional shares of no par value\ncommon stock to be offered to\nholders of the company\u2019s partici\npating class A stock held on\nrecord May 27, 1930. Proceeds\nwill be used in development and\nexpansion of the company\u2019s busi\nness and for other corporate\npurposes.\nDemand for patent medicines,\npharmaceuticals and other rem\nedies thus far in 1930 has not\nbeen equal to that of the same\nperiod of 1929, Standard Statistics\nCompany, of New York reports.\nThey believe, however, as a result\nof their survey, that trade will\nundergo a revival during the lat\nter part of the year.\nThe recent behavior of the\nstock market has undermined\nsome of the confidence in busi\nness improvement that had been\nestablished previous to the latest\nreaction of the New York Stock\nExchange, Gage P. Wright, New\nYork business and investment\ncounselor says in the current is\nsue of Business Economic Digest.\nHe added that many business\nmen today pay too much atten\ntion to the stock market for the\ngood of either themselves or\ntheir business. He advocated a\ncarefully planned business recov\nery.\nLarge scale production of elec\ntric welded pipe will be begun by\nthe Republic Steel Corporation at\nits new pipe mill at Youngstown\nwithin the next few weeks. Prac\ntically all machinery has been\ninstalled in the new mill.\nCommercial stocks of bituminous\ncoal used largely for Industrial\npurposes amounted to 33M00.000\ntons on April 1, 1930, according\nto the quarterly survey just com\npleted by the United States Bu\nreau of Mines. This is a de\ncrease of 7,200,000 tons from the\namount on hand at the beginning\nof the previous quarter. It is\nalso 3,800,000 tons less than the\ni quantity in storage on the same\ndate last year.\nThe General Railway Signal\nCompany has received one of the\nlargest contracts in the history\nof its business from the Toronto\nTerminal Company covering the\ninstallation of an extensive elec\ntric interlocking system for the\nnew terminal station facilities at\nToronto. The work is planned\nfor completion by July 1. 1931,\nunder rush program.\nSir Henry Thornton, K. B. E\u201e\nchairman and president of the\nCanadian National Railways, has\nbeen elected to the board of di\nrectors of the Union Guardian\nTrust Company, the oldest trust\ncompany in Detroit.\nAtlantic Gas and Electric Cor\nporation has purchased the\nI Dunkard Valley Oil and Gas Com\npany and certain gas acreage\ncontrolled by the Eddy interests\nin southwestern Pennsylvania. The\ncompany distributed natural gas\nat wholesale in Green county, Pa.\nOhio Southern Gas Company,\nhas commenced drilling opera\ni tions in new territory on the\nBig Sandy River, near Webb,\nI Wayne county, W. Va. Ohio\nSouthern Gm Company to a ento\n[\u2666siduary of Appalachian Gas Cor\ni poration.\nA decided upward trend in the\nconsumption of gasoline is fore-\nI cast by the recent Issuance of a\nsurvey of the industry made by\nStandard Statistics Company of\nNew York. The company esti\nmates that in 1930 there will be\n408,300,000 barrels of gasoline\nused and that in 1934 there will\nbe 536,500,000 barrels consumed.\nThe survey represents an average\nexpectancy of future probabilities\nbased on past trends operative\nover a long period.\nPennsylvania State Water Cor\nporation, a subsidary of Commun\nity Water Service Company, re\nports gross revenue of $1,036,294\nfor the twelve months ended\nMarch 31. 1930. After operating\nexpenses, maintainence. and taxes\nexcluding Federa* income tax,\nhad been deducted there re\nmained a balance of $624,950.\nMemphis Natural Gas Com\npany has announced that on\nJune 27, 1930, it will redeem all\nof its outstanding first mortgage\n6 per cent sinking fund gold\nbonds, amounting to $6,153,500,\ndated August 1, 1928, and due\nAugust 1, 1934, a. the principal\namount and accrued interest\nthereon, plus a premium of 3\nper cent of the principal amount,\nof the bonds.\nHackensack Water Company's\nfirst quarter earnings amounted\nto 70 cents a share on the com\nbined 95,125 shares of 7 per cent\nparticipating preferred and 205\n000 common shares. This com\npares with 22 cents a share on\n205,000 common shares after pre\nferred dividends in the like 1929\nperiod.\nThe American Rolling Mill-\nSheffield Steel Merger is to be on\na share for share basis for the j\nI common stock. No plan has been\nworked out yet for the exchange\nof preferred holdings.\nStandard Gas and Electric, for\nthe months ended March 31,\n1930, reports a total income of\n$76,894,036 after expenses and\nordinary taxes but before depre\nciation have been deducted. This\ncompares with $73,639,882 in the\nprevious 12 months.\nAnaconda Wire and Cable Com\npany, in the quarter ended March\n31, earned 14 cents a share.\nI I\nCoty, Incorporated, excluding,\nholdings in foreign subsidiaries.\nreported first quarter earnings of\n61 cents per share on 1,492,655.\nThis compares with 88 cents a\nshare on 1 330,079 shares in the\nlike 1929 quarter.\nSinclair Consolidated Oil Cor\nporation has contracted to ac\nquire Pierce Petroleum Corpora\ntion through an exchange of\nstock on the basis of a little\nover one share for each four'\nshares on Pierce common. The\nPierce stockholders are to vote\n-n the offer June 12.\nVulcan. Detinning .Company,\nfor the quarter ending March 31,\ni showed a net profit of $110,445\nafter depreciation, taxes, etc.,\nt had been deducted. This com-\npares with $164,563 in the first\nquarter of 1929.\nThe United Corporation, has\n1 offered to acquire a block of\napproximately 25 per cent of\ncommon stock of Columbia Gas\nand Electric Corporation on the\nbasis of one-third of a share of\n$3 preference stock bearing cumu\nlative dividends from July 1, 1930,\n1 and one and one-half shares of\nthe common stock of the United\nCorporation for each share of\ncommon stock of Columbia Gas\nr and Electric Company, ex the\nspecial dividend in voting trust\ncertificates representing shares\nof common stock of Columbia\ni Oil and Gasoline, which has been\ndeclared payable to holders of\nrecord May 24, 1930.\nNew England Gains\nIn Building Awards\nBOSTON. May 19.\u2014New build-\ning contracts awarded in New\nFngland during ttie second week\nof May were not only well above\n5 recent weeks, but also were higher\n5 than the corresponding week in\nmost previous years.\nDepartment store sales are on\nthe whole satisfactory in volume.\nSpecialty shops report business\nis spotty, resistance to current\n5 styles in women\u2019s clothing be\n-1 ing an important factor in this\nrespect.\ns The shoe business is subnormal:\nmost manufacturers are currently\noperating on part time, some im-1\nt provement is reported in cotton\n1 textiles, but operations on the\nwhole are still depressed.\nThe movement of freight on\nthe New England railroads con-\ntinues to run well below a year'\nago. Sales of jewelry at whole-\n5 sale so far in May have been\n10 per cent under the same\n1 period of last year.\n$86,000 Gold Comes\nIn at Port in Week\nNEW YORK. May 19. \u2014The\nj movement of gold at the Port of\nNew York for the week consisted\nof the receipt of $86,000, chiefly\nfrom Latin America. There were\nno exports. However, gold ear-\nj marked here for foreign account\nwas decreased by $2,000,000. A\ntotal of $5,280,000 of the metal\nentered the United States at San i\nF ancisco during the week, $4,- j\n825,000 coming from Japan and\nMW,006 from China.\nNEW M FIRM\nOPENS STOCK\nOFFICE\nThe New York Stock Exchange\nfirm of Prince and Whitely today\nopened their new office bn the\nsecond floor of the Washington\nBuilding, Fifteenth St. and New\nYork Ave. N. W. In addition to\nbeing marked by the opening of\nthe new office today, the firm is\nalso celebrating the fiftieth an\nniversary of their entry into\nWashington financial circles.\nThe first private wire system\nbetween Washington and New\nYork was inaugurated by the\nfirm which has been long asso\nciated with every big financial\n\u201cbreak\u201d that has come in half a\ncentury.\nOn July 2, 1881 a resident part\nner of the firm was in the old\nBaltimore and Ohio depot when\nPresident Garfield was assassi\nnated. He immediately went to\na nearby telegraph office and\nwired other members of the firm\nso that they could be ready for\nthe terrific blow received by the\nstock market when word was re\nceived later in the day.\nAn immense board room has\nbeen provided in the new quart\ners for the accommodation of\ncustomers. A number of inova\ntions have also been incorporated\nin the entire office, which is one\nof the best in the city.\nClarence F. Burton has been\nelected vice president and cash\nier of the Washington Mechanics\nSavings Bank to fill the vacancy\ncaused by the resignation some\ntime ago of Thomas J. Groom.\nHe will take his position as soon\nas he has returned from the an\nnual conclave of the District of\nColumbia Bankers Association at\nAsheville, N. C., next month,\nwhere he will serve as a repre\nsentative of the bank.\nThe new official is a life-long\nresident of Washington, being\nbom here in 1885. At present he\nlives in Chevy Chase: is a mem\nber of the Columbia Country\nClub and the Racquet Club, and\nis a lawyer admitted to practice\nbefore the United States Supreme\nCourt.\nFor the past year the new offi\ncer has been a member of the\nboard of directors of the institu\ntion. He will be located in the\nnew branch office of the bank on\nConnecticut Avenue.\nJohn B. Elliott, formerly a\nj Washington newspaperman and\ni now vice president and treasurer\nof the Jamieson Petroleum Com\npany, was a recent visitor in\nWashington financial circles.\nLaurence A. Slughter, vice presi\ndent of the Commercial National\nBank, has returned to his desk\nafter a visit to Atlantic City.\nOfficers, directors and employes\nof the Bank of Commerce and\nSavings held an outing yesterday\nat the Town and Country Club.\nJohn D. Mothershed is the new\nmanager of the local offices of\nFenner and Beane, according to\nrecent announcement. He suc\nceeds John McLean, who has been\ntransferred to St. Louis.\nEugene E. Thompson, of Crane,\nParris Co., here, was one of the\nprincipal speakers before the\nopening session of the convention\nqf Associated Stock Exchanges in\nMinneapolis, Minn., today. Mr.\nThompson represented the Wash\nington Stock Exchange.\nTwo special trains will be used\nby members of the District of\nColumbia Bankers\u2019 Association on\ntheir jaunt to Asheville. N. C.,\nwhere they will hold their annual\nconvention. The trains will leave\nUnion Station. Washington, at\n6 p. m. on June 4. according to\nClaude H. Woodward, chairman\nof the transportation. He said\nthat all of the latest accommoda\ntions will be incorporated in the\ntrains for the benefit of the\ntravelers.\nIt was decided to use two trains\nbecause of the fact that one long\ntrain would not be so comfort\nable for those journeying to the\nconvention.\nHarold N. Marsh, local attor\nney has been elected to the board\nof directors of the Liberty Na\ntional Bank, according to an\nnouncement made by George O.\nWalson, president of the insti\ntution. Marsh, a World War vet\neran, is a graduate of Harvard\nand George Washington Universi-\nI ties, and was admitted to the\nD. C. bar in 1916.\nQuarter of Income\nSpent for Foodstuffs\nNEW YORK, May 19.\u2014Ameri\ncans are spending one-fourth of\ntheir annual income for food and\nfoodstuffs, while their expendi\ntures for other necessaries totals\njust about one-third the amount\nconsumed for the \u201cdinner table,\u201d\na study by the General Foods\nCorporation shows.\nBased on its findings, the cor\nporation estimates the annual in\ncome of the United States at\namounts ranging from $78,000,-\n000,000 to $89,000,000,000, and of\nthis sum it calculates that the\nvalue of food purchased reaches\n$21,000,000,000 annually, plus\n$3,000,000,000 additional in prod\nucts \u201cconsumed on premises,\u201d in\ni eluding food raised and eaten on\nfarms and cleared through sag\nmart*\n21","height":"30194","width":"24213"}}
